text.tspan: Preservation of Orbital Forcing in
Incomplete Carbonate Successions
Research Question
How does incompleteness affects preservation of Milanković
signals in carbonate platforms?
Acknowledgements
The authors acknowledge the contribution of the CycloNet project, funded by the Research Foundation Flanders
(FWO, grant nr. W000522N).
Research Problem
Cyclostratigraphy is commonly used to derive age constraints
in pelagic and hemi-pelagic successions.
Low stratigraphic completeness of shallow-water environments
is considered problematic for cyclostratigraphic analyses.
Methods
We simulated carbonate platform growth for the duration of the Holocene (2.58 Myr) with the CarboCATLite model
(Burgess 2013) using Milanković driven generation of accomodation space. From the dip sections we calculated
stratigraphic completeness and ran spectral analyses (multi taper method) using only bed thickness information.
All code and data is available under www.doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.8312823 and on GitHub (scan QR code)
Take Home
There is
no obvious connection
between (in)completeness and preservation of Milanković signals
Summary
If accomodation space is forced by an orbital signal, bed
thickness of incomplete shallow-water carbonate succes
sions can record Milanković signals. Signal preservation
is equally good across the platform top due to high pro
duction rates and the flat geometry.
The signal is lost deeper in the basin, where beds are
amalgamated.
